And the artist will typically get somewhere between 15 percent and 20 percent of what's left after

915
01:01:17,840 --> 01:01:26,000
their 15 or 20 percent cut has fully paid back the record label for all the money that label has spent promoting them.

916
01:01:26,520 --> 01:01:28,480
So Apple's getting a straight 30.

917
01:01:28,480 --> 01:01:30,680
That's pretty straightforward of the 70.

918
01:01:30,720 --> 01:01:32,280
The label is getting the majority of it.

919
01:01:32,480 --> 01:01:34,400
The label is getting the majority of it.

920
01:01:34,600 --> 01:01:38,600
And the artist is getting anywhere from zero to maybe 10 percent.

921
01:01:38,600 --> 01:01:42,880
Something like that. Now, that sounds grossly unfair.

922
01:01:43,880 --> 01:01:54,160
What makes it less obviously unfair is that the record label is the one taking all of the financial risk in financing the music and very often

923
01:01:54,160 --> 01:01:55,920
paying for the artist's life.

924
01:01:56,680 --> 01:02:05,920
So in this economy, they are still the only companies that take a financial risk making original artwork.

925
01:02:06,440 --> 01:02:10,240
And they certainly deserve to be paid for taking that risk.

926
01:02:10,280 --> 01:02:11,600
So how does it work at Spotify?

927
01:02:11,720 --> 01:02:13,240
So now you paid your 10 bucks a month.

928
01:02:13,680 --> 01:02:16,120
How is that rent spread out?

929
01:02:16,200 --> 01:02:20,480
Sure. So what happens is you listen to music all month at the end of the month.

930
01:02:20,720 --> 01:02:33,040
Spotify looks at the amount of time that you spent listening to each of those songs and your ten dollars gets split pro rata to the originators of that

931
01:02:33,040 --> 01:02:37,520
music in roughly the same distribution as the 70 percent out of iTunes got split.

932
01:02:37,560 --> 01:02:40,400
Yes. How much does Spotify get to keep of the 10 bucks?

933
01:02:40,400 --> 01:02:40,920
30 percent.

934
01:02:40,960 --> 01:02:44,640
OK, so Spotify keeps 30 and the other 70 goes the same way, but now it's pro rata.

935
01:02:44,760 --> 01:02:46,320
Yeah, that's correct.

936
01:02:46,360 --> 01:02:59,160
And so for a consumer like you who maybe before Spotify was spending more than 10 dollars a month, it results in less financial benefit than it might have before.

937
01:02:59,160 --> 01:03:02,480
On the other hand, depends how much you listen to those songs.

938
01:03:02,840 --> 01:03:10,200
So if on Spotify, you know, if you buy the song on iTunes and you listen to it one time, you're paying a dollar twenty nine for one listen.

939
01:03:10,600 --> 01:03:16,760
But a lot of people, when they fall in love with the song, listen to it thousands of times and they listen to it for years.

940
01:03:17,200 --> 01:03:24,000
And if you take a dollar twenty nine and split it among thousands, effectively, they're paying very little each listen.

941
01:03:24,480 --> 01:03:29,000
So the paradigm shift is towards a pay for listen model.

942
01:03:29,520 --> 01:03:31,000
It's a consumption based payment.

943
01:03:31,120 --> 01:03:39,440
Now, back before any of this stuff came along, if you had a radio station and you played a song, not satellite radio, just straight FM radio, for example.

944
01:03:40,280 --> 01:03:42,360
Did you have to pay a royalty for that?

945
01:03:42,880 --> 01:03:50,480
The radio station had an agreement with an organization called a Performing Rights Society.

946
01:03:51,080 --> 01:03:56,040
These are societies that manage a particular type of right in music.

947
01:03:56,040 --> 01:04:05,400
So if you and I write a song, we and record it, we've just generated a whole basket of different types of legal rights, all of which we begin by owning.

948
01:04:05,720 --> 01:04:14,000
And then we can sell those rights off to different third parties that will help us collect the income that attaches to the exploitation of those rights.

949
01:04:14,520 --> 01:04:23,080
In the case of songs that get played on the radio or performed at a basketball game or these sorts of things, that right is called a public performance right.

950
01:04:23,640 --> 01:04:28,760
And the radio stations do deals with these rights societies in the US.

951
01:04:28,760 --> 01:04:32,080
The two most prominent ones are called ASCAP and BMI.

952
01:04:32,560 --> 01:04:39,920
And those organizations are responsible for monetizing that right on behalf of artists.

953
01:04:40,160 --> 01:04:52,840
So the radio station at the end of the year will give ASCAP a million dollars and then ASCAP will do something like Spotify does, which is tabulate what that million dollars corresponded to.

954
01:04:53,040 --> 01:04:57,080
And they'll pay out the royalties to artists pro rata in accordance with that.

955
01:04:57,480 --> 01:05:01,240
And Sean Parker was involved with Spotify and with Napster, right?

956
01:05:01,520 --> 01:05:01,920
That's right.

957
01:05:01,920 --> 01:05:07,080
So he had kind of a this was this was the evolution of what he and Sean Fanning had done.

958
01:05:07,080 --> 01:05:07,880
Yeah, it was.

959
01:05:07,880 --> 01:05:10,920
They had intended Napster to become a legal service.

960
01:05:11,200 --> 01:05:16,560
And what they wanted, you know, 20 years ago was to go do deals with the record labels to legalize it.

961
01:05:16,920 --> 01:05:25,120
But the industry was so defensive towards them and so aggressive that it couldn't happen.

962
01:05:25,440 --> 01:05:38,000
It took 20 years and it took the industry being decimated for everybody to be desperate enough that they were willing to entertain solutions to the Internet.

963
01:05:38,240 --> 01:05:39,640
And that's what Spotify was.

964
01:05:39,960 --> 01:05:46,920
You know, it's interesting when you look at all of the businesses that have been disrupted by the Internet and contrast it with those that have not.

965
01:05:47,040 --> 01:05:51,960
Right. So you've just given us a very eloquent description of how the music industry was disrupted.

966
01:05:51,960 --> 01:05:56,520
But you also pointed out something interesting, which is it wasn't just the Internet that disrupted.

967
01:05:56,800 --> 01:06:02,000
It was the desperation that followed the decimation that permitted the restructuring.

968
01:06:03,040 --> 01:06:06,000
Of course, then you can rattle off all the glib and obvious examples, right?

969
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:12,280
What Amazon has done to retail, what Netflix has done to, you know, blockbuster and, you know, stores on the side of the street,

970
01:06:12,720 --> 01:06:17,400
what Uber has done to taxis, what, you know, all of the travel sites have done to travel agents.

971
01:06:17,400 --> 01:06:19,200
I mean, it's been incredibly disruptive.

972
01:06:19,560 --> 01:06:27,200
And yet when I think about medicine, it's like one of the least disrupted industries by technology.

973
01:06:27,560 --> 01:06:30,840
And, you know, you basically still have hospitals eat all the rent.

974
01:06:31,360 --> 01:06:36,680
Payers, although most people generally perceive them as bad guys, generally don't get paid that much.

975
01:06:37,080 --> 01:06:40,360
Providers get less and less on a per encounter basis.

976
01:06:40,840 --> 01:06:45,760
And it's, you know, overall a pretty much similar system to what it was 20 years ago.

977
01:06:46,240 --> 01:06:47,680
And that's I don't know.

978
01:06:47,680 --> 01:06:55,080
I mean, I guess I'd have to think about it, but I can't think of too many industries that are as unchanged in the presence of this revolution as health care.

979
01:06:55,440 --> 01:06:56,480
No, I think you're right.

980
01:06:57,040 --> 01:07:02,480
The appeal of investing in health care is exactly what you just expressed.

981
01:07:02,480 --> 01:07:04,600
And that's what drew me into it several years ago.

982
01:07:05,160 --> 01:07:09,880
And what I've learned since then has been slightly disillusioning.

983
01:07:10,480 --> 01:07:11,880
But I'll give you my take on it.

984
01:07:12,600 --> 01:07:21,680
The first thing I would say is that health care is still an industry that largely gets paid through labor.

985
01:07:22,120 --> 01:07:30,120
So most of the money ultimately goes to labor, goes to doctors, it goes to health care personnel.

986
01:07:30,760 --> 01:07:33,280
The hospitals don't make that much money.

987
01:07:33,280 --> 01:07:34,920
They're not that great a business.

988
01:07:34,960 --> 01:07:41,840
You know, if you look at Kaiser, for example, which is an integrated payer provider in California, I think they have a three or four percent.

989
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:42,840
Gross margin.

990
01:07:43,400 --> 01:07:45,440
It's not a phenomenal business.

991
01:07:45,840 --> 01:07:49,040
The payers, to your point, have very low margins.

992
01:07:49,120 --> 01:08:05,120
They in fact have legally imposed limits on the amount of gross margin that they can generate, which, you know, you can argue about the ethics of the pharmaceutical companies who everyone hates seemingly extract enormous profits.

993
01:08:05,480 --> 01:08:08,760
On the other hand, it's a very competitive industry.

994
01:08:09,080 --> 01:08:23,960
And apart from the legalized monopoly given to them via patents on new drugs, they are the only companies, sort of as I said about record labels, they're the only ones who are out here designing new solutions.

995
01:08:24,120 --> 01:08:25,600
And taking an enormous risk.

996
01:08:25,680 --> 01:08:26,800
Taking an enormous risk.

997
01:08:26,800 --> 01:08:33,200
And their shareholders are taking that risk now, whether they're being overpaid or underpaid to take that risk is totally debatable.

998
01:08:34,120 --> 01:08:43,120
The other thing is that it's unclear where technology can deliver dividends in terms of human health.

999
01:08:43,680 --> 01:08:50,880
And so we're thinking about medicine at a moment in which we as a species have already made enormous progress.

1000
01:08:50,880 --> 01:08:54,080
I mean, whatever we've doubled or tripled lifespan.

1001
01:08:54,080 --> 01:08:56,320
And, you know, I mean, you know these numbers better than I do.

1002
01:08:56,320 --> 01:09:08,160
But even if you get rid of the infant mortality factor and these other things that distort the numbers, people are living quite a bit longer on average than they were even seemingly 30 years ago.

1003
01:09:08,560 --> 01:09:14,480
And that's especially true of affluent societies until they get afflicted by the diseases of affluence.

1004
01:09:15,280 --> 01:09:26,320
So where can we get more life from or where can we reduce suffering and disease by way of technology is a little unclear.

1005
01:09:26,800 --> 01:09:39,360
There are all sorts of things that we could, of course, do to make hospitals more efficient and to spend less than we do on things like end of life care that maybe aren't a good use of capital.

1006
01:09:40,160 --> 01:09:45,920
But there's not so obviously a Spotify of health care waiting to happen.

1007
01:09:45,920 --> 01:09:57,760
It's more like there are a million little IT operating efficiencies that McKinsey consultants will over the next several decades implement in large health organizations.

1008
01:09:58,480 --> 01:10:09,360
And then the big promise is around new types of medicine that I think will arise in the biotechnology industry.

1009
01:10:09,360 --> 01:10:12,240
And that's where I'm now spending a lot of my time and attention.

1010
01:10:12,240 --> 01:10:26,080
Yeah, it's sort of interesting because I think one of the challenges of health care and I think this was most evident during the debates many years ago, not many, but what I call it eight, ten years ago around the ACA and around complete revisiting a restructuring of health care.

1011
01:10:26,080 --> 01:10:34,160
And one of the things I found a little painful in listening to politicians talk about health care was they spoke about it like there was just one problem to be solved.

1012
01:10:34,160 --> 01:10:42,840
But the way I sort of think about it is there are at least three completely separate but highly related problems, which is quality of care.

1013
01:10:43,240 --> 01:10:45,640
And that can be broken down into two levels.

1014
01:10:45,640 --> 01:10:50,960
You can sort of have it as just keeping people from dying versus like generating alpha.

1015
01:10:50,960 --> 01:10:53,280
So, you know, really improving quality.

1016
01:10:53,720 --> 01:10:56,720
There's cost, which is just the cost to the system.

1017
01:10:56,720 --> 01:11:07,240
And about 90 percent of the dollars are basically spent by three entities, the government, the employer and the payer, depending on who's at risk.

1018
01:11:07,800 --> 01:11:10,680
The consumer is on the hook for about 10 percent of that cost.

1019
01:11:10,960 --> 01:11:12,360
So how could you reduce the cost?

1020
01:11:12,880 --> 01:11:15,560
And then the third leg of that stool is access.

1021
01:11:15,840 --> 01:11:17,600
How do you ensure access?

1022
01:11:18,400 --> 01:11:22,840
And so when we talk about technology disrupting health care, it's like, where do you start?

1023
01:11:22,840 --> 01:11:29,600
Right. Because, you know, for me, I can see things where technology can be quite helpful on quality of care.

1024
01:11:30,120 --> 01:11:33,960
Not entirely obvious to me how to leverage technology to lower cost.

1025
01:11:33,960 --> 01:11:36,120
People much smarter than me, I'm sure, think about that.

1026
01:11:36,520 --> 01:11:41,160
And not entirely clear, at least at a practical level, how it can drive access.

1027
01:11:41,440 --> 01:11:46,760
Although in theory, that should be the first place you'd want to go after leveraging technology.

1028
01:11:46,760 --> 01:11:52,440
But I think I'm trying to think about what you said about how Spotify went about it and trying to see is there a parallel there?

1029
01:11:52,440 --> 01:11:56,560
Because the thing with Spotify that was hard was you had multiple constituents, right?

1030
01:11:56,560 --> 01:12:02,200
You have artists, you have labels, you have consumers and they all kind of want something a little different.

1031
01:12:02,320 --> 01:12:06,120
And that speaks of an optimization problem, which is clearly what health care is.

1032
01:12:06,760 --> 01:12:14,160
But going on what you said a moment ago, it sounds like today you're a little less encouraged than you would have been four years ago.

1033
01:12:14,160 --> 01:12:15,480
And you're thinking on this problem.

1034
01:12:16,200 --> 01:12:36,520
Well, let me try and recapitulate your three legs of the stool in one simple framework, which is something that we should all be aiming for is to generate universal access to the current best available health care that anyone in the world receives.

1035
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:44,640
You know, one of my favorite quotes, I always forget who's quoted is, but venture capitalists talk about it a lot, which is that the future is already here.

1036
01:12:44,640 --> 01:12:46,240
It's just not evenly distributed.

1037
01:12:46,720 --> 01:12:48,360
And I think that's almost always true.

1038
01:12:48,600 --> 01:12:55,360
Look at what rich people are doing and assume that in 20 or 30 years, everybody will have that.

1039
01:12:56,120 --> 01:12:58,200
And so what are rich people doing right now?

1040
01:12:58,200 --> 01:13:14,080
Well, they're paying doctors like you a lot of money to do very bespoke types of medicine that leverage all sorts of deep biometric analysis of their bodies, a lot of thinking by you and your team.

1041
01:13:14,960 --> 01:13:33,880
And a lot of spend on the usage of what are currently expensive machines, MRI machines to do preventative screening for tumors every year, things like this that if you're really rich, you know, you might as well go get an MRI every year, get a full body MRI every year.

1042
01:13:33,880 --> 01:13:35,600
I mean, just see if there's anything going on.

1043
01:13:35,600 --> 01:13:36,280
Why not?

1044
01:13:37,080 --> 01:13:53,560
And so what stands between today and orphans in Somalia receiving that level of care and what stands in the way I think is to some degree, a level of technological leverage.

1045
01:13:54,160 --> 01:14:11,480
What is happening in your head when you look at a patient's blood tests and try to gel that with your biophysiological mental models is something that I believe computers will be able to do in the future.

1046
01:14:11,880 --> 01:14:24,280
And so right now we use physicians for thinking and for bedside manner and for guidance.

1047
01:14:24,640 --> 01:14:37,680
And then we use some physicians like surgeons for physical procedures that they're essentially athletes at, you know, you want high performing athletes who don't mess up, who are very precise, who've done it a million times.

1048
01:14:38,680 --> 01:14:49,080
Well, the roboticization of physical medicine like surgery is something that I believe will just continue to get better and better.

1049
01:14:49,080 --> 01:14:50,280
It may take longer.

1050
01:14:50,280 --> 01:14:56,880
It may not be replaceable immediately, but that will, you know, we will be primarily doing robotic surgeries 100 years from now.

1051
01:14:57,680 --> 01:15:13,680
The cognitive work that physicians do will, I believe, largely be replaced by computational systems that can leverage the same types of theoretical frameworks that our minds are utilizing to make good decisions.

1052
01:15:14,280 --> 01:15:22,480
And what you're left with is all the touchy feely personal stuff that you as a physician and any other physician knows really matters.

1053
01:15:23,080 --> 01:15:24,780
It's not superficial.

1054
01:15:25,180 --> 01:15:48,180
The ability to help someone make good decisions about their own health, to make someone care about their physical health, to help them navigate difficult decisions that aren't straightforward that involve trade-offs are the sort of things that physicians right now don't have the time to do that they did when they were taking their medicine bag around to people's houses and hanging out for a couple hours.

1055
01:15:48,580 --> 01:15:58,980
And so in a certain way, we may go back to an older style of medicine, but the people who do that may look more like highly skilled nurses than like physicians.

1056
01:15:59,180 --> 01:16:16,680
So I believe that what you'll see is globally a lot more technology involved in the deployment of medicine and a shift in the composition of the labor market around medicine towards something that looks more like a large population of highly skilled nurses.

1057
01:16:16,680 --> 01:16:27,480
Fewer overpaid or appropriately paid, but maybe overtrained physicians that right now are very scarce that only rich people can access.

1058
01:16:28,080 --> 01:16:32,380
And then most excitingly, you're going to see a lot of new medicine.

1059
01:16:32,880 --> 01:16:35,680
That's the stuff I'm focused on now as an investor.

1060
01:16:35,980 --> 01:16:39,080
And that's the stuff that I think is going to be the most game changing.

1061
01:16:39,080 --> 01:16:42,480
That's the stuff that's going to buy us years of additional life.

1062
01:16:42,480 --> 01:16:51,780
So when did you make that transition where you sort of your big foray into this was obviously Spotify as far as like transition one.

1063
01:16:51,780 --> 01:16:58,280
So DA 2.0 to DA 3.0 and then DA 4.0 doing the investing.

1064
01:16:58,280 --> 01:17:01,180
So the biotech stuff specifically, when did you make that transition?

1065
01:17:01,980 --> 01:17:05,180
Well, I'm still making it because it's a hard transition to make.

1066
01:17:05,180 --> 01:17:09,980
And there's been so much that I've already had to learn and so much more that I have yet to learn.

1067
01:17:10,980 --> 01:17:31,980
I think the starting point was this realization that what mattered most in healthcare as a capital allocator, meaning the most useful place that I could help direct money was to what goes through the pipes of the healthcare system as opposed to the healthcare system itself.

1068
01:17:32,980 --> 01:17:41,780
The healthcare system in America for the reasons we've just discussed is a creaky old infrastructure.

1069
01:17:41,780 --> 01:17:49,280
And it's important to fix it just like it's important to fix the government or the broken bridges that we have all over the country.

1070
01:17:49,280 --> 01:17:52,580
But it's not the most interesting thing to do.

1071
01:17:53,180 --> 01:18:04,380
And it also doesn't have a global impact because fixing the US healthcare system doesn't do a lot for folks in Sudan or in Saudi Arabia or in Japan or anywhere else.

1072
01:18:04,380 --> 01:18:13,380
You're just dealing with a human system where what's broken are the human structures that we've constructed to deliver the thing.

1073
01:18:13,380 --> 01:18:19,180
So that was my starting point was realizing that the medicine itself was the thing that mattered more.

1074
01:18:19,780 --> 01:18:30,580
And ultimately, despite all of the valuable things that physicians do, the biggest game changers in human health in the past 50 years have been pills.

1075
01:18:30,580 --> 01:18:43,380
They've been pills that very brilliant people invent and that we can give to people through any number of channels and that actually fix the problem sometimes.

1076
01:18:44,080 --> 01:18:58,580
And we're moving into an era of medicine that people call preventative medicine or precision medicine or whatever you want that really boils down to addressing illness at the level of mechanism.

1077
01:18:58,780 --> 01:19:16,180
Understanding that diseases have a functional concrete explanation and that we can develop interventions that actually fix what's broken in a very precise way and without a lot of collateral damage.

1078
01:19:16,180 --> 01:19:23,780
And our ability to do that better and better is what's going to give people much more health in the future.

1079
01:19:23,780 --> 01:19:28,780
And we're in inning two or one of that journey.

1080
01:19:28,780 --> 01:19:39,780
So as an investor, there couldn't be a more exciting place to hang out and the advances that we're making on a monthly or yearly basis are staggering.

1081
01:19:40,380 --> 01:19:55,380
So when I noticed that that was happening in the world, it just became clear to me that this was not only an exciting and interesting place to be, but also one that could be enormously profitable both financially and in terms of the benefit to humanity that delivered.

1082
01:19:55,380 --> 01:20:01,380
What got you interested in the problem of living longer personally?

1083
01:20:01,980 --> 01:20:14,980
Well, I guess I am not primarily preoccupied with living longer or with longevity as I am with the reduction of suffering that already exists.

1084
01:20:14,980 --> 01:20:30,980
And so people who are really obsessed with longevity, maybe you are one of them, will make the argument that death is the great tragedy of human life and that we basically don't realize it's so bad because we take it for granted and can't see any other way.

1085
01:20:31,980 --> 01:20:34,980
And I think that's an alternative.

1086
01:20:34,980 --> 01:20:43,980
That may be right, but I also think there's a lot of evidence in nature that death and the turnover of populations has some utility.

1087
01:20:43,980 --> 01:20:52,980
Steve Jobs talked about famously that this is nature's way of clearing out the old ideas and bringing in new ones and creating urgency and creating urgency.

1088
01:20:52,980 --> 01:21:08,580
I just think that there are enough people dying obviously prematurely from things that should be preventable and there are lots of people dying in the second half of their life or suffering from things that should be preventable that we should start by focusing on those things.

1089
01:21:08,580 --> 01:21:34,180
Now, it may be the case that longevity is the skeleton key to all of those problems, that the number one risk factor for all diseases is age and that if we could just figure out what's happening with aging, then we could get out in front of all these other diseases as it was said in the last video.

1090
01:21:38,580 --> 01:21:50,580
So what are you most passionate about right now? Not necessarily from the investment thesis perspective but from the technology or promise that the idea holds up.

1091
01:21:50,580 --> 01:22:02,580
Well, the holy grail for me is approaching what I think of as a singularity-like moment in the world.

1092
01:22:02,580 --> 01:22:08,580
People throw around the term singularity mean all sorts of things but I actually believe it's useful.

1093
01:22:08,580 --> 01:22:10,580
Who coined it?

1094
01:22:10,580 --> 01:22:26,580
You know, it may have been Kurzweil, Ray Kurzweil, or I'm not sure, or it may have been some of those old cybernetics dudes like Robert Boehner.

1095
01:22:26,580 --> 01:22:30,580
I first heard it from Ray's work, I don't know enough.

1096
01:22:30,580 --> 01:22:34,580
Why don't you explain briefly how he's referring to it?

1097
01:22:34,580 --> 01:22:44,580
Well, I think Ray Kurzweil is referring to the singularity as this moment when human minds merge with machines.

1098
01:22:44,580 --> 01:23:00,580
And so we, for example, download our brains into computers and then are effectively immortalized because our consciousness exists now in a digital format.

1099
01:23:00,580 --> 01:23:04,580
That's not the singularity I'm talking about.

1100
01:23:04,580 --> 01:23:16,580
But the concept of a singularity is that this is a moment at which sort of everything changes and there's an almost infinite acceleration in our capacity to do something.

1101
01:23:16,580 --> 01:23:36,580
The singularity that I envision in our understanding of biomedicine is the moment at which we can digitally represent complex biology and therefore study it at zero marginal cost.

1102
01:23:36,580 --> 01:23:48,580
So let me explain this right now. What we essentially do in biology and what medicine has always tried to do is understand how the machine of a living system works.

1103
01:23:48,580 --> 01:23:56,580
And in the work you do on metabolism, for example, the ways that we try to represent how the machine works are incredibly complicated.

1104
01:23:56,580 --> 01:24:04,580
There are these flow charts with all these arrows and pictures and this connects to this and this connects to these 10 things.

1105
01:24:04,580 --> 01:24:10,580
And if you pull this lever, these four things happen. And how do we even make sense of that?

1106
01:24:10,580 --> 01:24:25,580
A way station to the singularity I'm talking about is the field of so-called systems biology in which what people do is they observe these biological systems and then they try to translate the mechanistic of the system.

1107
01:24:25,580 --> 01:24:54,580
And then they try to translate the mechanistic connections that they have uncovered into code, into formal representations, into a formal language that captures how something works in a way that a computer can understand and in a way that is unambiguous and not sort of stifled by the inherent ambiguity of human language, by which we describe a lot of these things in everyday life.

1108
01:24:54,580 --> 01:25:06,580
And ultimately, systems biology, I think, will allow us to simulate biological systems in their full, glorious complexity.

1109
01:25:06,580 --> 01:25:12,580
And when we can do that, which we might be 20 years away from or we might be a thousand years away from, I don't know.

1110
01:25:12,580 --> 01:25:23,580
But once we can do that, then we can effectively run intervention-based experiments on digital systems at zero cost.

1111
01:25:23,580 --> 01:25:33,580
And that would be the moment at which we will start to understand biology and the ways that we can intervene in it at an extraordinary rate.

1112
01:25:33,580 --> 01:25:42,580
Until then, unfortunately, we have to do tests on humans or mice or dogs or monkeys.

1113
01:25:42,580 --> 01:25:46,580
And unfortunately, we can only learn one thing at a time that way.

1114
01:25:46,580 --> 01:25:51,580
We do controlled experiments where we hold everything constant except one variable.

1115
01:25:51,580 --> 01:25:55,580
And in so doing, we try to understand how that variable works.

1116
01:25:55,580 --> 01:25:58,580
And this is a very slow way of learning.

1117
01:25:58,580 --> 01:26:00,580
And it's a very expensive way of learning.

1118
01:26:00,580 --> 01:26:21,580
And although the people who participate in clinical trials are heroes to whom we owe most of our medicine, clinical trials are a brutal form of learning that cause many people to die from experimental medicines or that cause many people to endure enormous suffering without any benefit.

1119
01:26:21,580 --> 01:26:30,580
And so that's the thing I'm most excited about, getting to that singularity of digitally representing complex biology.

1120
01:26:30,580 --> 01:26:38,580
Most of the things that I'm focused on as an investor, I view as somehow being stepping stones towards that singularity.

1121
01:26:38,580 --> 01:26:45,580
If you look at other fields that could benefit from the ability to do digital experiments, consider macroeconomics.

1122
01:26:45,580 --> 01:26:50,580
Wouldn't macroeconomics be even more complicated than biology?

1123
01:26:50,580 --> 01:26:54,580
In other words, this sounds like the hardest problem I've ever heard of.

1124
01:26:54,580 --> 01:27:08,580
All of these systems people put in the same bucket of complex adaptive systems, kind of ground zero for studying these things is the Santa Fe Institute, an organization in which I'm involved and I'm very passionate about.

1125
01:27:08,580 --> 01:27:14,580
And part of the reason I'm passionate about all of these types of systems is because they share certain characteristics.

1126
01:27:14,580 --> 01:27:20,580
So in a kind of vague way, they're all complex in just the colloquial sense.

1127
01:27:20,580 --> 01:27:23,580
Like they're really complicated. There are a lot of moving parts.

1128
01:27:23,580 --> 01:27:33,580
But it may turn out that we can come up with theories that actually describe all of these types of systems.

1129
01:27:33,580 --> 01:27:46,580
So there's some sense in which these problems of economies and the weather and physiological systems are all kind of similar.

1130
01:27:46,580 --> 01:27:55,580
And we may be able to come up with theories that are predictive that help us make predictions about these different types of systems.

1131
01:27:56,580 --> 01:28:02,580
So that's a kind of intellectual promise land that I think is worth chasing.

1132
01:28:02,580 --> 01:28:10,580
Whether or not it's going to happen or not, I think even trying for those sorts of theories is going to generate useful information.

1133
01:28:10,580 --> 01:28:15,580
Whether we'll be able to simulate these things or not is sort of an open theoretical question.

1134
01:28:16,580 --> 01:28:26,580
But I'm optimistic about it because it seems like it's the logical endpoint of all of our digital technologies to create digital representations of reality.

1135
01:28:26,580 --> 01:28:36,580
And on the one hand, reality is really complex. But on the other, it seems to be driven at the bottom from relatively simple theories.

1136
01:28:37,580 --> 01:29:00,580
And so to the extent that the laws of physics are ubiquitous and are driving everything from the bottom up and that everything that happens subsequent to the laws of physics are these emergent phenomena, it's not clear to me that we won't come up with simple parsimonious descriptions of these types of systems.

1137
01:29:01,580 --> 01:29:09,580
And the physics of the universe before Newton probably also appeared intractably chaotic.

1138
01:29:09,580 --> 01:29:25,580
So the way that anything looks to us before we understand it is, I think, pretty imposing, which is why when we have breakthroughs, they feel almost like this enormous relief because something that seemed really complicated becomes really simple.

1139
01:29:26,580 --> 01:29:33,580
Yeah. I mean, the obvious example would be the coding of the human genome, which is now approaching 20 years in its anniversary.

1140
01:29:33,580 --> 01:29:45,580
Do you feel that that discovery has underperformed, overperformed, or met expectations on what we would have thought prior to that codification?

1141
01:29:45,580 --> 01:29:57,580
The pithy aphorism that I think applies to genomics and a lot of things in technology is that it's probably short-term overestimated and long-term underestimated.

1142
01:29:57,580 --> 01:30:14,580
So certainly, when the Human Genome Project reached its initial milestones in Craig Venter's genome being sequenced, there was an extreme optimism that was unjustified that now that we've cracked this code, we're going to figure out everything.

1143
01:30:14,580 --> 01:30:22,580
In five or ten years, clearly that has not happened. And so to that extent, those predictions have failed.

1144
01:30:23,580 --> 01:30:43,580
On the other hand, the sequencing technology that underwrote that is now being used to sequence mRNA, to sequence methylation of the genome, to sequence neoantigens in cancer patients' tumors.

1145
01:30:44,580 --> 01:30:52,580
This has become an extraordinarily useful set of tools for reading all kinds of biology.

1146
01:30:52,580 --> 01:31:12,580
And so long-term, I believe the impact of the human genome and our understanding of it is almost impossible to overstate because it represents a basic part of a toolkit that is now integral to everything at the core.

1147
01:31:14,580 --> 01:31:18,580
Yeah, so in other words, the tool might actually be more valuable than the initial application.

1148
01:31:18,580 --> 01:31:27,580
Absolutely. But the only way that people were able to justify pain for that tool was in this

1149
01:31:27,580 --> 01:31:29,580
In the hope.

1150
01:31:29,580 --> 01:31:41,580
In the hope. That's what I say about Bitcoin and stuff, by the way, as well, because this is now part of my theory of technology, which is that you take something like Bitcoin and all these blockchains and all of this.

1151
01:31:42,580 --> 01:31:48,580
I was an early investor in this company, Ripple, about six years ago now. And so I've been interested in all of this for years.

1152
01:31:48,580 --> 01:31:55,580
But I don't take the view that there's any end point I predict and know with any level of confidence.

1153
01:31:55,580 --> 01:32:10,580
All I can tell you is that having the smartest computer science 19-year-olds in the world in mass shift their attention to an area of technology is going to produce something.

1154
01:32:11,580 --> 01:32:17,580
So whether Bitcoin becomes a replacement for the United States dollar is almost irrelevant.

1155
01:32:17,580 --> 01:32:23,580
What I'm interested in is what's going to happen now that millions of people are working on this thing.

1156
01:32:23,580 --> 01:32:29,580
Similarly, the Human Genome Project was this kind of catalyzing event. It's very vivid.

1157
01:32:29,580 --> 01:32:33,580
Bill Clinton had a press conference with Craig Venter and it got everyone excited.

1158
01:32:34,580 --> 01:32:47,580
And that sort of moment is what inspires a lot of 18-year-olds or a lot of 15-year-olds to go into molecular biology undergraduate programs and then to become genetics researchers.

1159
01:32:47,580 --> 01:32:54,580
And so this is how history happens. And a lot of things have already come out of genomics and will continue to.

1160
01:32:54,580 --> 01:33:01,580
Have you been paying a lot of attention? I mean, you alluded to it a moment ago, but have you just on a personal level been paying a lot of attention to the liquid biopsy space?

1161
01:33:01,580 --> 01:33:05,580
A lot. Yeah. I've been following the liquid biopsy space now for about four years.

1162
01:33:05,580 --> 01:33:10,580
Yeah. You and I spoke about this a couple of years ago and I wasn't sure how much you'd still been into it.

1163
01:33:10,580 --> 01:33:22,580
This is something that's very interesting to me. You know, one of the things I talk about with patients is even with my most best attempts at providing the most bespoke insights into how to prevent diseases.

1164
01:33:22,580 --> 01:33:35,580
When you take a big step back and say, let's look at the three main diseases that are going to kill most people in a civilized society where you're basically taking care of the blocking and tackling that you've alluded to earlier.

1165
01:33:35,580 --> 01:33:39,580
It's atherosclerotic diseases, it's cancers and neurodegenerative diseases.

1166
01:33:39,580 --> 01:33:46,580
And my personal viewpoint is that the atherosclerotic diseases and the neurodegenerative diseases, we have much more insight into how to prevent.

1167
01:33:47,580 --> 01:33:55,580
Cancer is tough. And I sort of explained to people when you look at a blood test and let's talk about the best blood test money can buy.

1168
01:33:55,580 --> 01:34:08,580
It's probably offering you 70 to 80 percent of your predictive value on the atherosclerotic side, probably offering you 60 to 70 percent of your predictive value on the neurodegenerative side.

1169
01:34:08,580 --> 01:34:17,580
It probably isn't offering you even 30 percent of insight on cancer because, of course, the mutations that kill are somatic, not germline.

1170
01:34:17,580 --> 01:34:23,580
So we're not measuring those. We don't have great assays for measuring adoptive immune cell function.

1171
01:34:23,580 --> 01:34:28,580
We can measure innate immunity, but that's so crude and it's irrelevant in cancer.

1172
01:34:28,580 --> 01:34:46,580
And so we talk about something else you alluded to, which is how aggressive can we be in screening whilst solving for or optimizing around minimizing physical harm and emotional harm, physical harm from the actual screening tool, emotional harm from risk of false positives, because the harder you look, the more you'll find.

1173
01:34:46,580 --> 01:34:53,580
And the open, gaping open hole in this is we can't do a liquid biopsy.

1174
01:34:53,580 --> 01:35:01,580
So we got interested in this together, you and I mutually, around this enox two protein, which was quite interesting.

1175
01:35:01,580 --> 01:35:05,580
But unfortunately, that company, that technology doesn't really seem to exist right now.

1176
01:35:05,580 --> 01:35:09,580
It also had a number of issues with it. But basically, it was a Western blot. It was a protein assay.

1177
01:35:09,580 --> 01:35:13,580
They were looking at a protein, this enox two protein.

1178
01:35:13,580 --> 01:35:27,580
And the belief was that that protein was found exclusively on malignant cells and could only be shed off not just cancer cells, but cancer cells that had the potential to spread and attach to other cells.

1179
01:35:27,580 --> 01:35:34,580
Now, a company that we both know pretty well, GRAIL, is taking a different approach that seems slightly more logical. Tell us a little bit about GRAIL.

1180
01:35:35,580 --> 01:35:43,580
GRAIL is an interesting company. It's a spin out of Illumina, which is the behemoth genome sequencing business.

1181
01:35:43,580 --> 01:35:58,580
They make all the machines that do sequencing that most people use. And the premise of GRAIL is that by sequencing peripheral blood, you can find all sorts of cellular refuse from somatic tissues.

1182
01:35:58,580 --> 01:36:08,580
And that this refuse, if you are able to amplify it, will tell you about the cells that it's coming from.

1183
01:36:08,580 --> 01:36:23,580
And so one of the proofs of principle of this concept in general was noninvasive prenatal screening. Pregnant women have in their blood, I think, potentially 10% of their peripheral blood is actually coming from the fetus.

1184
01:36:23,580 --> 01:36:38,580
And so you can detect a lot of things about the fetus by looking at the mother's peripheral blood. And in that case, maybe what you need to effectively do is separate the 10% from the 90% in order to look at it.

1185
01:36:38,580 --> 01:36:52,580
When you're talking about early cancers, you might be dealing with sub half percent or sub 10th of a percent concentrations of tumor DNA that are showing up in the blood.

1186
01:36:52,580 --> 01:37:07,580
And so the premise of GRAIL is that if you sequence the blood with enough depth, meaning you sequence it over and over and over again, you can detect just that DNA that's coming from the tumor.

1187
01:37:07,580 --> 01:37:18,580
And by doing so, you can identify things about it that give you a guide to where the tumor is and what its genetic characteristics are.

1188
01:37:19,580 --> 01:37:28,580
And this is much harder than what you just said a moment ago because the problem you described earlier has two things going for it, which is one, you've got much more of it there.

1189
01:37:28,580 --> 01:37:40,580
Let's just assume the number is 10%. But the other thing is half of that DNA is foreign. 50% of that DNA is from the father, 50% is from the mother. So you have half foreign greater quantity.

1190
01:37:40,580 --> 01:37:50,580
If you have colon cancer and we are lucky enough to get the RNA or DNA of that colon cancer, it might have 20 mutated genes. It's effectively self DNA.

1191
01:37:50,580 --> 01:37:52,580
Well, it is self DNA.

1192
01:37:52,580 --> 01:37:53,580
Exactly.

1193
01:37:53,580 --> 01:37:54,580
But it's maybe tumor DNA.

1194
01:37:54,580 --> 01:37:55,580
It's tumor DNA.

1195
01:37:55,580 --> 01:37:56,580
Which is still a self tumor.

1196
01:37:56,580 --> 01:38:03,580
Yeah, exactly. So I mean, that's a double whammy. It's not just a needle in a haystack. It's like a needle of hay in a haystack.

1197
01:38:03,580 --> 01:38:05,580
That's correct. And it's also difficult because...

1198
01:38:05,580 --> 01:38:07,580
I just came up with that, by the way. I'm really proud.

1199
01:38:07,580 --> 01:38:09,580
That's the first smart thing I think I've ever said.

1200
01:38:09,580 --> 01:38:11,580
The needle of hay in the haystack.

1201
01:38:11,580 --> 01:38:12,580
I like that.

1202
01:38:12,580 --> 01:38:13,580
You can use that as much as you want.

1203
01:38:13,580 --> 01:38:24,580
I will. I'm going to start right now. When you're looking for that needle of hay in the haystack, the premise of your search has to be that you know what you're looking for.

1204
01:38:24,580 --> 01:38:46,580
In other words, you have to identify a series of potential oncogenes in which you're seeking aberrant genetic variants that would indicate the gene has essentially been co-opted by the disease and is now working for the cancer as opposed to working for you who want to defeat the cancer.

1205
01:38:46,580 --> 01:39:04,580
And there are so many different ways that this technology is going to be difficult. That is matched by billions of dollars that people are investing in this because solving this problem is, as the company's name suggests, sort of a grail.

1206
01:39:04,580 --> 01:39:09,580
I'm not an investor in grail, but I've looked at them. And I've also looked at many of their competitors.

1207
01:39:09,580 --> 01:39:22,580
There's another approach that's really cool that I'm investing in right now. A company out of Boston called Glimpse is a business that was founded by Sangeeta Bhatia, who's an extraordinary researcher at MIT.

1208
01:39:22,580 --> 01:39:32,580
Sangeeta is a hepatologist, but a bioengineer whose work has uncovered two really interesting ideas that I think are useful in cancer screening.

1209
01:39:32,580 --> 01:39:46,580
One is that when cancer is setting up shop in a tissue, it remodels the micro environment so as to build defenses for itself against the immune system and against the other physiological processes that would stand in its way.

1210
01:39:46,580 --> 01:40:01,580
And it turns out that there are in the human genome 550 different endoproteases that are in some combination utilized in the remodeling of tissues in different processes.

1211
01:40:01,580 --> 01:40:13,580
So they're used primarily in healthy processes. But when cancers are beginning, these proteins get recruited or these enzymes get recruited rather to do this remodeling work.

1212
01:40:13,580 --> 01:40:37,580
They're sort of the construction workers of the disease as it gets set up. And Sangeeta's work and the work of several other researchers that she's leveraging has identified what proteases tend to be implicated in the early formation of different diseases ranging from fatty liver disease to liver cancer to lung cancer and a set of others.

1213
01:40:37,580 --> 01:40:59,580
And if you can, it turns out, identify 10 or 15 enzymes that you basically only see upregulated enormously when a particular disease is beginning, then there's another way of detecting it that Sangeeta is working on, which is to engineer nanoparticles that you send into the body.

1214
01:40:59,580 --> 01:41:10,580
She calls them a synthetic biomarker. You let them circulate and you design them such that they break apart if they encounter those enzymes.

1215
01:41:10,580 --> 01:41:18,580
And when they break apart, they fragment into smaller nanoparticles that can be detected in the urine.

1216
01:41:18,580 --> 01:41:34,580
So Sangeeta's approach is rather than look for these trace amounts of refuse in the blood, why not send essentially a team, a SWAT team into the body to circulate and hunt for a thing?

1217
01:41:34,580 --> 01:41:43,580
And if that SWAT team finds the thing, get a much larger signal in the urine. I think that's a very elegant approach.

1218
01:41:43,580 --> 01:41:45,580
Will that have tissue specificity?

1219
01:41:45,580 --> 01:41:57,580
It'll have tissue specificity to the extent that the disease you're looking for has a different enzymatic signature when it's in different tissues.

1220
01:41:57,580 --> 01:42:14,580
Got it. So in the context of, let's say you get the signal and you would have to believe then that you're going to have different enzymatic pathways in the mesenchymal system of colon cancer versus lung cancer.

1221
01:42:15,580 --> 01:42:29,580
I see. So it's not, you know, when you were saying this, I wasn't, I'm not familiar with the glimpse. So I was, I was wondering if what you're going to say was it got taken up in residence and then you basically would do, you know, it was labeled with gadolinium or something and you do an MRI and you'd say, well, hey, this stuff is being broken apart in the lung.

1222
01:42:29,580 --> 01:42:35,580
Therefore, that's where we want to look. But that's not what you're saying. No, this is all happening in the periphery in the blood itself.

1223
01:42:36,580 --> 01:42:47,580
The breakup of the nanoparticles is occurring at the site of the disease, but the refuse from that interaction is going through the kidneys and into the urine.

1224
01:42:47,580 --> 01:42:54,580
It would be interesting if there was a way to see if there's a way to capture the local signature at the tissue site of origin.

1225
01:42:54,580 --> 01:43:05,580
There may in fact be ways to do this and there are several nanoparticle based approaches that follow the lines that you described where it's an imaging agent that is meant to bind specifically to the tissue.

1226
01:43:05,580 --> 01:43:19,580
What's cool about this though is you don't need to target. You just use the circulatory system to get these things everywhere. And if they detect the thing that you're probing, they change. And that's what you measure.

1227
01:43:19,580 --> 01:43:29,580
I think this is a really clever workaround for some of the problems that I think have been bedeviling liquid biopsy. But I do think liquid biopsy will probably work.

1228
01:43:29,580 --> 01:43:35,580
And the other reason it may work, and there's a company called Freenome, for instance, that's taking a different angle on it.

1229
01:43:35,580 --> 01:43:49,580
Freenome's approach is don't look for the tumor DNA in the blood. Look at the entire genome and see if there is any sort of smoke from the fire.

1230
01:43:49,580 --> 01:44:00,580
If the cancer is the fire, try to detect the body's systemic response to the cancer and recognize that as aberrant.

1231
01:44:00,580 --> 01:44:10,580
In other words, even if the cancer itself is sending off a very small signal, maybe the systemic response to it is a much larger signal and you can detect that.

1232
01:44:10,580 --> 01:44:20,580
So people are going to try and get after this in many different ways. My prediction is that within a decade, we'll have one or more of these that work quite reliably.

1233
01:44:21,580 --> 01:44:32,580
And each of us will, at our annual physical, have a routine blood test that is pretty good at detecting cancer. Now, that begets another problem that people have raised, which is, you know, what if we're all getting cancer all the time?

1234
01:44:32,580 --> 01:44:46,580
And most of the time, the immune system is disposing of it in short order. If that's happening, then we'll have another problem to solve, which is how do we know when we should treat people who are detected early versus when shouldn't we?

1235
01:44:47,580 --> 01:44:52,580
But that's fine. Problems create solutions which create more problems. And that's what we do.

1236
01:44:52,580 --> 01:44:59,580
You know, that's the problem that I probably worry about the most. I mean, I guess the second most. The problem I worry about the most is can we crack this?

1237
01:44:59,580 --> 01:45:13,580
But that problem I got this glimpse into with all the deep dive I did into Oncoblot three years ago, which was I was asked by a company that was interested in acquiring them to help with the due diligence.

1238
01:45:13,580 --> 01:45:36,580
I actually thought it was complete buffoonery, total quackery, complete and utter nonsense. But after about a year and a half, I thought there really was something there that unfortunately had been sort of bastardized by unsavory characters that were involved in basically creating kind of a profit center around selling alternative products that were complete nonsense.

1239
01:45:37,580 --> 01:45:47,580
But when we did our own analyses on raw data that they gave us, we saw something pretty interesting. There's two questions you have to ask when you're doing this.

1240
01:45:48,580 --> 01:46:05,580
The first is, and rather than describe them in terms of sensitivity, specificity, negative predictive value and positive value, just describing this stuff in English, you want to understand something, which is if you do a blood test on a person and it comes back and says nothing, how confident are you that they have nothing?

1241
01:46:06,580 --> 01:46:18,580
That's the concept of negative predictive value. And then conversely, if the test comes back and says you have something, how confident can you be that you have something? That's the idea of positive predictive value.

1242
01:46:19,580 --> 01:46:31,580
Now, if you look at how OncoBlot was created and you look at how the FDA gave it a type of approval, which is not an FDA approval, but there's, you know, and I don't want to get into the weeds on that stuff.

1243
01:46:32,580 --> 01:46:46,580
But basically it was approved, quote unquote, only for patients presenting with metastatic cancer of it with an unknown primary because of its remarkable ability to create a differentiation around 27 different types of tissue.

1244
01:46:46,580 --> 01:46:56,580
So someone shows up with a lung nodule that's not lung cancer. It's actually important to know is that breast? Is it thyroid? Is it what? Because they could have a primary that's occult, but it's still metastatic cancer.

1245
01:46:56,580 --> 01:47:15,580
And this is a life and death decision as to how to treat it. And that's where OncoBlot was actually very useful. And so OncoBlot became really, really good. If someone had cancer and you did a blood test on them, you had about 99.4% likelihood of correctly guessing, not just that they had cancer, but what kind of cancer it was.

1246
01:47:15,580 --> 01:47:24,580
But the flip side is really important, which is if you take a whole bunch of people that don't have cancer and you can only do this out of a blood bank prospectively, you can't even do this in the population.

1247
01:47:24,580 --> 01:47:33,580
What's the likelihood that you're not going to be over calling cancer? And when we did an analysis and it was not a huge analysis, we were limited by the amount of data we had.

1248
01:47:34,580 --> 01:47:55,580
What we saw was by about 5x, it overestimated the prevalence of cancer at a given age for a given histology. And our interpretation of that was either this is categorically useless or it's picking up a bunch of cancers that don't go on to become cancers.

